Definition: Code for the agency which analyzed the sample
The ratio of reflected to incident light.
Areal coverage of the plant Asteridae
The portion of streamflow (discharge) that is supplied by groundwater sources.
Areal coverage of the plant Batis maritima
The battery temperature of a datalogger or sensing system
The battery voltage of a datalogger or sensing system, often recorded as an indicator of data reliability
Total mass of phytoplankton, per unit area or volume
Classification of material encountered by a driller at various depths during the drilling of a well and recorded in the borehole log.
Areal coverage of the plant Borrichia frutescens
Bulk electrical conductivity of a medium measured using a sensor such as time domain reflectometry (TDR), as a raw sensor response in the measurement of a quantity like soil moisture.
Carbon dioxide (CO2), raw data from sensor
DEPRECATED -- The use of this term is discouraged in favor of the use of the synonymous term "Carbon, particulate organic".
Color in quantified in color units
The phytoplankton pigment Chlorophyll a allomer
The concentration of colored dissolved organic matter (humic substances)
The identifying number for a water sampler container.
The chlorophyll a concentration contributed by cryptophytes
Areal coverage of the plant Cuscuta spp.
The chlorophyll a concentration contributed by Dinoflagellates
Distance measured from a sensor to a target object such as the surface of a water body or snow surface.
Areal coverage of the plant Distichlis spicata
The amount of water that could be evaporated and transpired if there was sufficient water available.
The number of fish identified by the detection equipment
A counter which counts the number of  datalogger flash memory errors
Water level with regard to an arbitrary gage datum (also see Water depth for comparison)

Solar radiation, direct and diffuse, received from a solid angle of 2p steradians on a horizontal surface. 
Source: World Meteorological Organization, Meteoterm
Groundwater depth is the distance between the water surface and the ground surface at a specific location specified by the site location and offset.
Carbonate hardness also known as temporary hardness
The combination effect of heat and humidity on the temperature felt by people.
Difference in the  2H:1H ratio between the sample and standard

Soil reponse of a reflected standing electromagnetic wave of a particular frequency which is related to the dissipation (or loss) of energy within the medium. This is the imaginary portion of the complex dielectric constant.
Areal coverage of the plant Iva frutescens
Latitude as a variable measurement or observation (Spatial reference to be designated in methods).  This is distinct from the latitude of a site which is a site attribute.
The effect of moisture settling on the surface of a leaf as a result of either condensation or rainfall.
Areal coverage of the plant Limonium nashii
Longitude as a variable measurement or observation (Spatial reference to be designated in methods). This is distinct from the longitude of a site which is a site attribute.
A counter of the number of times the battery voltage dropped below a minimum threshold
Langelier Saturation Index is an indicator of the degree of saturation of water with respect to calcium carbonate
Areal coverage of the plant Lycium carolinianum
Areal coverage of the plant Monanthochloe littoralis
Outgoing rate of heat energy transfer minus the incoming rate of heat energy transfer through a given area
Organic Kjeldahl (organic nitrogen + ammonia (NH3) + ammonium (NH4)) nitrogen
Difference in the 15N:14N ratio between the sample and standard
Dissolved oxygen, raw data from sensor
Difference in the 18O:16O ratio between the sample and standard
Parameter related to a hydrologic process.  An example usage would be for a starge-discharge relation parameter.

Permittivity is a physical quantity that describes how an electric field affects, and is affected by a dielectric medium, and is determined by the ability of a material to polarize in response to the field, and thereby reduce the total electric field inside the material. Thus, permittivity relates to a material's ability to transmit (or "permit") an electric field.

pH is the measure of the acidity or alkalinity of a solution. pH is formally a measure of the activity of dissolved hydrogen ions (H+).  Solutions in which the concentration of H+ exceeds that of OH- have a pH value lower than 7.0 and are known as acids.
Pheophytin (Chlorophyll which has lost the central Mg ion) is a degradation product of Chlorophyll
Measurement of phytoplankton with no differentiation between species
Position of an element that interacts with water such as reservoir gates
Precipitation such as rainfall. Should not be confused with settling.
Pressure relative to the local atmospheric or ambient pressure
A unique data recorder program identifier which is useful for knowing when the source code in the data recorder has been modified.
Total amount of incoming radiation from all frequencies
Total amount of outgoing radiation from all frequencies
A measure of the intensity of rainfall, calculated as the depth of water to fall over a given time period if the intensity were to remain constant over that time interval (in/hr, mm/hr, etc)

Soil reponse of a reflected standing electromagnetic wave of a particular frequency which is related to the stored energy within the medium.  This is the real portion of the complex dielectric constant.
A code used to identifier a data recorder.
Areal coverage of the plant Salicornia bigelovii
Areal coverage of the plant Salicornia virginica
A counter of events in a sequence

Signal-to-noise ratio (often abbreviated SNR or S/N) is defined as the ratio of a signal power to the noise power corrupting the signal. The higher the ratio, the less obtrusive the background noise is.
Silicate.  Chemical compound containing silicon, oxygen, and one or more metals, e.g., aluminum, barium, beryllium, calcium, iron, magnesium, manganese, potassium, sodium, or zirconium.
The depth of water if a snow cover is completely melted, expressed in units of depth, on a corresponding horizontal surface area.
Areal coverage of the plant Spartina alterniflora
Areal coverage of the plant Spartina spartinea
The volume of water flowing past a fixed point.  Equivalent to discharge
Areal coverage of the plant Suaeda linearis
Areal coverage of the plant Suaeda maritima
A counter which counts the number of datalogger table overrun errors
Time domain reflextometry, apparent length divided by probe length. Square root of dielectric
The THSW Index uses temperature, humidity, solar radiation, and wind speed to calculate an apparent temperature.
The THW Index uses temperature, humidity, and wind speed to calculate an apparent temperature.
Carlson Trophic State Index is a measurement of eutrophication based on Secchi depth
The pressure of a vapor in equilibrium with its non-vapor phases
The difference between the actual water vapor pressure and the saturation of water vapor pressure at a particular temperature.
The velocity of a substance, fluid or object
Volume. To quantify discharge or hydrograph volume or some other volume measurement.
Volume of liquid water relative to bulk volume. Used for example to quantify soil moisture
A counter which counts the number of total datalogger watchdog errors
Water depth is the distance between the water surface and the bottom of the water body at a specific location specified by the site location and offset.
Water depth averaged over a channel cross-section or water body.  Averaging method to be specified in methods.
Water level relative to datum. The datum may be local or global such as NGVD 1929 and should be specified in the method description for associated data values.

Water potential is the potential energy of water relative to pure free water (e.g. deionized water) in reference conditions. It quantifies the tendency of water to move from one area to another due to osmosis, gravity, mechanical pressure, or matrix effects including surface tension.
The height of a surface wave, measured as the difference in elevation between the wave crest and an adjacent trough.
Flow rate from well while pumping
The pressure exerted by the fluid at the wellhead or casinghead after the well has been shut off for a period of time, typically 24 hours
The effect of wind on the temperature felt on human skin.
The length of flow of air past a point over a time interval. Windspeed times the interval of time.
Drag or trangential force per unit area exerted on a surface by the adjacent layer of moving air
